{{ill|Temmon Hakase|lt=Doctor of Astrology|ja|天文博士|1=Tenmon Hakase|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is a topic related to __NOINDEX__  [[Onmyodo]]

Later, [[Emperor Tenmu]] was such a master of astrology and fugue that he took his own divination tools and told fortunes during the [[Jinshin War]]. He also had a deep knowledge of the yin-and-yang five phases philosophy, which led to the establishment of the Bureau of Onmyō and Japan's first [[observatory]] in 676, and the use of the term "onmyōji" in 685, which further increased the popularity of the yin-and-yang five phases philosophy. In 718, the [[Yōrō Code]] established the Bureau of Onmyō as an internal department of the Ministry of Center, and when it was stipulated that the positions of {{ill|Temmon Hakase|lt=Doctor of Astrology|ja|天文博士|1=Tenmon Hakase|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Onmyō Hakase|lt=Doctor of Onmyō|ja|陰陽博士|1=Onmyō Hakase|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, onmyōji, {{ill|Reki Hakase|lt=Doctor of Calendar|ja|暦博士|1=Reki Hakase|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Rōkoku Hakase|lt=Doctor of Water Clock|ja|漏刻博士|1=Rōkoku Hakase|qq=draft|qq=draft}} should be permanently assigned as technical officers, the Bureau of Onmyō became officially in charge of divination along with the [[turtle shell]] diviners who belonged to the [[Department of Divinities]].


{{Cite shortage|date=October 2019}}
'''Tenmon Hakase''' ({{ill|Tenmon Hakase|lt=天文博士|ja|天文博士|1=Tenmon Hakase|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) was a teaching position established in the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under Japan's [[Ritsuryō system]], responsible for matters of {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (astronomy). The position was equivalent to {{ill|Junior Seventh Rank|lt=Junior Seventh Rank, Lower Grade|ja|正七位下|1=Senior Seventh Rank|lt=Senior Seventh Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with one appointee, though later an assistant position ({{ill|Gonkan|ja|権官|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) was also created.

== Overview ==
The Tenmon Hakase's duties included observing celestial phenomena (e.g., {{ill|lunar eclipses|ja|月食|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|comets|ja|彗星|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and other {{ill|astronomical events|ja|天文現象|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). If an anomaly was detected, the Tenmon Hakase would consult astronomical texts, interpret omens, and present a sealed report to the emperor in the {{ill|Tenmon Missō|ja|天文密奏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ritual. The role also entailed instructing ten {{ill|Tenmonsei|ja|天文生|qq=draft|qq=draft}} students in astronomy. Notably, the Tenmonsei were forbidden to access astronomical texts, as specified under the {{ill|Miscellaneous Orders|ja|雑令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}’s section on the prohibition of secret texts ({{ill|Hisogenzō|ja|秘書玄象条|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). Consequently, only the Tenmon Hakase and a few other authorized individuals could read these texts.

From the mid-{{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, following instruction from {{ill|Kamo no Yasunori|ja|賀茂保憲|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was appointed Tenmon Hakase. Thereafter, the position became hereditary, controlled by the {{ill|Abe clan (Onmyōdō)|ja|阿倍氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (specifically the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).

== References ==
* Hitoshi Satō, "Tenmon Hakase," in *{{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 9* (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1988) ISBN 978-4-642-00509-8.
* Hitoshi Satō, "Tenmon Hakase," in *Heian Jidai-shi Jiten* (Kadokawa Shoten, 1994) ISBN 978-4-04-031700-7.

